In JCL, a COND parameter can be incorporated into the JOB statement or EXEC statement. This parameter can be used to skip steps based on return codes from previous steps. Here, we are testing the return code from the previous job steps. In the event that the test is deemed to be true, the current job step execution is bypassed. Bypassing a job step is not an abnormal termination, but simply an omission. COND is coded in JOB statement: Every step of the job is tested when COND is coded into a JOB statement. At any given job step, if the condition is true, it is bypassed along with the subsequent steps.
COND is coded in EXEC statement: In case COND is coded in the EXEC statement of a job step and finds to be true, only that job step will be skipped, and execution will continue from the next job step. COND is coded in JOB statement: Every step of the job is tested when COND is coded into a JOB statement. At any given job step, if the condition is true, it is bypassed along with the subsequent steps. COND is coded in JOB statement: COND is coded in EXEC statement: In case COND is coded in the EXEC statement of a job step and finds to be true, only that job step will be skipped, and execution will continue from the next job step. COND is coded in EXEC statement: Example: Example: //MATEKSD JOB MSGLEVEL=(1,1),NOTIFY=&SYSUID, COND=(0,NE)
//STEP01   EXEC PGM=CONDPGM1
//STEP02   EXEC PGM=CONDPGM2,COND=(0,EQ)
//STEP03   EXEC PGM=CONDPGM3,COND=(4,EQ) //MATEKSD JOB MSGLEVEL=(1,1),NOTIFY=&SYSUID, COND=(0,NE)
//STEP01   EXEC PGM=CONDPGM1
//STEP02   EXEC PGM=CONDPGM2,COND=(0,EQ)
//STEP03   EXEC PGM=CONDPGM3,COND=(4,EQ) Explanation of COND=(0 NE) Explanation of COND=(0 NE) As you can see, the COND parameter is set to (0,NE) at the JOB level. In particular, it will check if the return code 0 does not equal the return code of any of the steps in JCL? If this is true, then the job should be terminated. As a result, if any of the steps (such as STEP01, STEP02, or STEP03) returns a non-zero return code, this condition will be true and the job will be terminated.

